The Chronicle Innocent Kurira, Sports Reporter THE darts community will bid farewell to one of its loyal sons as they lay to rest one of the best players the country has produced, Moses Ndlovu. Ndlovu (65) died last Wednesday and will be laid to rest at Umvutsha Park Cemetery this morning.
Popularly known as “Uncle Moses”, the late Ndlovu represented Zimbabwe at various competitions. He was also a founding member of Old Nic Darts Club. <img class="wp-image-542390 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/darts.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/darts.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2021/04/darts-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> National Darts Association of Zimbabwe (Ndaz) “We extend heartfelt condolences to the Ndlovu family, friends and darts fraternity at large. We used to call him ‘Uncle Moses’. He was a high ranked darts player in Bulawayo Metropolitan Provincial Darts Association as well as a national player for many years. “His untimely passing has truly shocked the entire darts fraternity.
“He had problems with his health last month, he was down at home but we never thought it would be this bad. We lost Uncle Moses around 13.00hrs today (February 15, 2023) at Central Hospital in Bulawayo.  “For and on behalf of National Darts Association of Zimbabwe (Ndaz) I offer deepest sympathy to all his loved ones and I pray that the almighty comforts you in this time of grief and immeasurable loss,” reads a statement from Ndaz. — @innocentskizoe